<br>
When approaching enemy territory is it better to 1) run at full speed to get where you are going as fast as possible OR 2) move cautiously through trees and undergrowth (risking getting separated from the group)?<br>
<br>
Is there any way to &quot;detect&quot; hidden or stealthy snipers?<br>
<br>
Is there any way of readily identifying the enemy at a distance other than individually selecting them and reading their stats?<br>
<br>
What class specific tips can be offered to us up-coming members?  What should we be specializing in and developing in andicipation of RvR?  e.g for a Skald is there any advantage to using Sword over Axe or Hammer?  For Healers - what are the most advantageous spells and strategies?  What should be AVOIDED (if anything) as we apply our XP to skills?  For casters is it better to use DeBuff spells over DD spells?  Id really like to see basic advice for each of the Midgard classes.  Also some indication as to what Class / capability is MOST NEEDED by the guild.<br>
<br>
Beyond that, I already know the 1st two rules of RvR:<br>
  1) Dont get killed.<br>
  2) When the above fails, die with dignity.<br>
but any other advice is welcome <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4F4F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/uvoluptarius.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Voluptarius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lad/Lass</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#F2CF7E>(12/17/01 4:39:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmaclearfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> First two basic steps ...</span><hr size=1> Like getting ready to jump into a swiming pool that is a little on the cold side, you gotta just jump in! Just start doing it.<br>
<br>
The biggest danger to look out for, is to not die as an experience death. And that is caused by other critters. An 'aggressive' critter that cons 'grey' to you will not attack you, unless you attack it.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#676767><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/utorgeirr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Torgeirr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>High Councellor</span><br>  Posts: 83<br> <font color=#F2CF7E>(12/17/01 7:57:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmaclearfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Gisli's 3 rules of RvR</span><hr size=1> I'll suggest 3 rules (that's as many as any barbarian can manage, eh?).  They can take you pretty far in RvR (or in life, for that matter :-)).<br>
<br>
1) Get good maps.  There are links from the Siol Lear page to the Coven Nex maps of the frontier.  I've found them more than adequate for anything I've wanted to do.<br>
<br>
2) Follow your leader. Depending on what type of RvR you do, chances are you are rarely alone.  In fact, chances are your group is with other groups.  What you want is to find a good war leader, and then do what they say. Likewise at the group level. If you don't have faith in the raid leader and/or the group leader, go elsewhere.<br>
<br>
3) Don't get in over your head. This means don't do things like charge into a horde of enemies, let an enemy pull you into a horde via /stick, etc.  I made some posts about this in on of the threads on our guild raid, so I won't repeat the details here.<br>
      -- Gisli<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/utorgeirr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Torgeirr</A> at: 12/17/01 7:58:57 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4F4F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ukvinnehok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kvinnehok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lad/Lass</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#F2CF7E>(12/17/01 9:10:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmaclearfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Gisli's 3 rules of RvR</span><hr size=1> I have a couple things to add to that.<br>
<br>
1)  FOLLOW ORDERS.  Do what your group leader tells you to do, not what you see people shouting to do.  Your group leader will take his orders from the battle commander and relay those to his group.  It makes his job easier, and your chances of winning, much better if everyone follows orders.<br>
<br>
2)  DO NOT GET AHEAD OF YOUR GROUP LEADER.  Unless told by your group leader to go scout or do something else, stay with your group and do not get separated.  You fight as a group, you live as a group, and you often die as a group.  But running off half-cocked is dangerous and self-defeating.  This is my personal No. 1 pet peeve, and not necessarily anyone else's. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Class Information:  All classes have their good points in RvR.  I am far from being an expert, but here is what I've noted:<br>
<br>
Healers:  Aside from healing the group and resing everyone possible, healers help greatly by mezzing and stunning the enemies.  And as far as I'm concerned, you can never have too many healers.<br>
<br>
AE Casters:  I've lumped this group together for obvious reasons, but it mostly pertains to thanes, runemasters and shamans.  AE spells are extremely beneficial.  That is mostly how our forces get wiped out trying to take keeps.  They can be cast through the gates and can kill a LOT of people.  Also, if you hurt an enemy with a spell, even if you don't kill them with it, you will get some realm points if and when they are killed.  There are different kinds of AE spells which have different advantages.  The runemasters and thanes get nice direct damage spells that can really wipe out a party.  Shaman spells are not so damaging, but their poison ae dots can prevent casters from casting and archers from shooting.<br>
<br>
Tanks:  There is no substitute for beating the crap out of an enemy with sheer brute force.<br>
<br>
Spiritmasters:  This is one class we are sorely in need of.  First of all, spiritmasters can send pets through a gate to attack the enemy.  But even more importantly, their pets can see a stealthed enemy even after they have hidden themselves.  Once that pet is targeted on the player, they can't get it off until it kills them, or they kill it.  That is by far our best way to get snipers at this time unless we are lucky enough to catch them and kill them before they hide.<br>
<br>
Skalds:  Skalds are very necessary as well.  One of their main functions, of course, is speeding us all to our deaths!  But skalds can also stun, snare, do a lot of damage with their spells, and they make good tanks.<br>
<br>
Hunters/Shadowblades:  These classes are the best all-around RvR solo classes.  There are many different philosophies regarding what to specialize in, although by far the most popular ones are the &quot;grief&quot; hunters, or those who choose stealth and their weapons as the two things they put the most points into.  I was killed by an enemy shadowblade-type with one backstab, and I never saw him coming.  And we all know the dangers of a good sniper running around our frontiers.<br>
<br>
As far as what you &quot;should&quot; specialize in, specialize in what you like to do.  It is all useful, and who knows, we may find other uses no one has thought about yet!<br>
<br>
Moomba <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#676767><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ulafittemaclear.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lafitte MacLear</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lad/Lass</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#F2CF7E>(12/18/01 7:52:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmaclearfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Melee who need to know</span><hr size=1> If you or one in your group are hit by a lone sniper, then here is a great tip that mostly hunters and casters use. It is the /face macro. Ever since they shortened the range of /stick, it is not so easy for melee to find that crased archer. Now melee can /face if you are hit, or /assist &lt;name&gt; return key, /face return key, run in that direction while continually hitting /face till your target is in sight. At that point stick to your target and use sprint to stay on their tail. No need to save endurance since you will be able to take them out easily once engaged.<br>
<br>
This works best when you are in the frontiers hunting and a lone sniper thinks she or he can terrorize us. <br>
<br>
<br>
